<subSubSection type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">In the Berlese Collection the following slides are present: 141/5, 8 from the &quot;Gardino di Boboli&quot;, Florcnce; and 141/9 from Pisa. The last-mentioned specimen is designated as type, although Berlese (1904a) mentioned &quot;Boboli&quot; as type-locality; I collected indeed topotypes in the &quot;Gardino&quot;.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
I do not know if Sellnick's (1928, p. 40) description of 
<taxonomicName authority="Michael, 1898" authorityName="Michael" authorityYear="1898" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Hoploderma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clavigera">Hoploderma clavigera</taxonomicName>
indeed represents the species; the same applies to 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Phthiracarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutulentus">Phthiracarus lutulentus Sellnick</taxonomicName>
(1920, p. 37).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
